GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 932
Short Title: Ten Percent Raise/Teachers/First Responders. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative A. Jones.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT ESTABLISHING THE 2025 TEACHERS' AND FIRST RESPONDERS' PAY
3 INCREASE PROGRAM TO PROVIDE A TEN PERCENT RAISE TO TEACHERS AND
4 FIRST RESPONDERS.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6
7 PART I. FIRST RESPONDER PAY INCREASE PROGRAM
8 SECTION 1.1. The following definitions apply in this Part:
9 (1) Base salary. – The regular, recurring annual compensation of a first responder,
10 excluding overtime pay, shift differentials, longevity pay, or any other
11 supplemental forms of compensation.
12 (2) Employing authority. – A State agency or a city, county, or other local
13 political subdivision of this State that employs first responders.
14 (3) First responder. – A public employee whose primary duties involve the
15 protection of life, property, or public safety during emergency situations,
16 including specifically:
17 a. Law enforcement officers.
18 b. Firefighters.
19 c. Emergency medical services personnel.
20 d. Public safety telecommunicators or dispatchers.
21 e. Nurses employed by public hospitals, health departments, correctional
22 facilities, or other government healthcare facilities.
23 (4) Pay increase. – A permanent increase to the base salary of a first responder at
24 the rate of ten percent (10%) of the first responder's current base salary.
25 (5) Public employee. – A person employed by an employing authority.
26 (6) Years of service. – The total number of years that a first responder has been
27 employed in a qualifying position by any employing authority within the
28 State.
29 SECTION 1.2. Appropriation for First Responders' Pay Increase. – There is
30 appropriated from the General Fund to the Reserve for First Responder Pay Increases the sum of
31 seven hundred million dollars ($700,000,000) in each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium to
32 provide a permanent ten percent (10%) pay increase to eligible first responders as defined in this
33 act. The Department of Public Safety and the Department of Health and Human Services shall
34 distribute these funds to employing authorities based on the total cost of implementing a ten
35 percent (10%) pay increase for all eligible first responders employed by each authority. Funds
*H932-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 distributed under this section shall be used exclusively for providing the mandated pay increase
2 to eligible first responders and may not be used for administrative costs or other purposes. The
3 pay increase provided pursuant to this section shall be added to the first responder's base salary,
4 effective July 1, 2025, and included in the first responder's base salary for purposes of calculating
5 future salary increases. This pay is subject to retirement contributions as provided by the
6 applicable retirement systems.
7 SECTION 1.3. Administration. – The Office of State Budget and Management shall
8 coordinate with the Department of Public Safety and the Department of Health and Human
9 Services to distribute funds to employing authorities by no later than August 15 of each fiscal
10 year within the 2025-2027 biennium. Employing authorities shall implement the pay increase for
11 eligible first responders effective July 1 of each fiscal year. To be eligible for the pay increase, a
12 first responder must be employed by an employing authority on July 1 of the fiscal year in which
13 the pay increase takes effect. First responders who work less than full time shall receive a
14 prorated pay increase based on the percentage of full-time equivalent hours worked. The Office
15 of State Budget and Management shall develop simplified procedures for the allocation and
16 distribution of pay increase funds and shall provide necessary guidance to the Department of
17 Public Safety and employing authorities. Employing authorities shall certify to the Department
18 of Public Safety the total cost of implementing the pay increase for eligible first responders by
19 August 1 of each fiscal year. By January 15 of each fiscal year, employing authorities shall submit
20 a verification that the pay increase has been implemented for all eligible first responders. Any
21 funds not expended for the purposes specified in this section by the end of each respective fiscal
22 year shall revert to the General Fund.
23
24 PART II. TEACHERS' PAY INCREASE PROGRAM
25 SECTION 2.1. Definition. – For purposes of this Part, the term "teacher" means a
26 classroom teacher, instructional support personnel, principal, or assistant principal employed by
27 a local school administrative unit, charter school, or regional school.
28 SECTION 2.2. Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the General Fund to the
29 Reserve for Teachers' Pay Increases the sum of nine hundred million dollars ($900,000,000) in
30 each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium to provide a permanent ten percent (10%) pay
31 increase to eligible teachers in the public schools. The Department of Public Instruction shall
32 distribute these funds based on the total cost of implementing a ten percent (10%) pay increase
33 for all eligible teachers employed by each entity. Funds distributed under this section shall be
34 used exclusively for providing the mandated pay increase to eligible teachers and may not be
35 used for administrative costs or other purposes. The pay increase provided pursuant to this section
36 shall be added to the teacher's base salary, effective July 1, 2025, included in the teacher's base
37 salary for purposes of calculating future salary increases, and is subject to retirement
38 contributions as provided by applicable retirement systems. This pay is subject to all applicable
39 federal and State withholding taxes.
40 SECTION 2.3. Administration. – The State Board of Education and the Department
41 of Public Instruction shall establish procedures and guidelines for the administration of the
42 teacher pay increase program consistent with this Part, in coordination with the Office of State
43 Budget and Management. The Department of Public Instruction shall distribute these funds to
44 local school administrative units, charter schools, and regional schools no later than August 15
45 of each fiscal year within the 2025-2027 biennium. To be eligible for the pay increase, a teacher
46 must be employed by a local school administrative unit, charter school, or regional school on
47 July 1 of the fiscal year in which the pay increase takes effect. Teachers who work less than full
48 time shall receive a prorated pay increase based on the percentage of full-time equivalent hours
49 worked. Local school administrative units, charter schools, and regional schools shall certify to
50 the Department of Public Instruction the total cost of implementing the pay increase for eligible
51 teachers by August 1 of each fiscal year. By January 15 of each fiscal year, local school
